{"Body":"<p>There are a more interesting example from russian language. It's pair <strong>класть</strong>  and <strong>положить</strong>. A literary version permits only <strong>класть</strong> for imperfective form and <strong>положить</strong> for perfective.</p>\n\n<p>Unliterary <strong>покласть</strong> (perfective) and <strong>ложить</strong>(imperfective) were also acceptibale in the 19th century.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=%D0%BA%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C,%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C&amp;year_start=1800&amp;year_end=2000&amp;corpus=12&amp;smoothing=3\" rel=\"nofollow\">класть vs ложить</a>\n<a href=\"http://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=%D0%BF%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B6%D0%B8%D1%82%D1%8C,%D0%BF%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C&amp;year_start=1800&amp;year_end=2000&amp;corpus=12&amp;smoothing=3\" rel=\"nofollow\">положить vs покласть</a>\n(sorry, I can't post the images with my reputation counter)</p>\n\n<p>Perhaps this is the really example of grammaticalization.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Класть</strong> cognate with the \"to loot\", <strong>ложить</strong> with the \"to lie (lay, lain)\". But this words have become synonymous in russian.</p>\n", "Id":"1768", "ParentId":"1663", "LastEditorUserId":"911", "CreationDate":"2012-04-08T10:48:17.807", "OwnerUserId":"911", "PostTypeId":"2", "comments":[], "LastEditDate":"2012-10-09T17:55:15.247", "LastEditedUser":{"UpVotes":"0", "WebsiteUrl":"https://github.com/pinocchio964", "Id":"911", "AccountId":"163311", "CreationDate":"2012-04-08T10:10:45.733", "AboutMe":"<p>franciscan programmer</p>\n", "Age":"29", "Location":"Ryazan', Russia", "DownVotes":"0", "Views":"1", "Reputation":"141", "DisplayName":"pinocchio964", "LastAccessDate":"2013-03-30T19:57:05.617"}, "LastActivityDate":"2012-10-09T17:55:15.247", "Score":"4", "CommentCount":"1", "OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"0", "WebsiteUrl":"https://github.com/pinocchio964", "Id":"911", "AccountId":"163311", "CreationDate":"201